      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement in the US, spanning from the 1950s to the 1960s, was a pivotal struggle against racial segregation and discrimination. Key highlights include the 1954 Brown v. Board of Education ruling that declared segregation in public schools unconstitutional, the Montgomery Bus Boycott of 1955-1956 led by Martin Luther King Jr., the 1963 March on Washington where King delivered his iconic \"I Have a Dream\" speech, and the 1964 Civil Rights Act that outlawed discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin. The movement was marked by nonviolent protests, civil disobedience, and the courageous efforts of activists who fought for equality and justice for African Americans.",
      "source": "target",
